        </div>
        <p>
          The app was really simple at first, just a sign-in page and a simple key-value table of the user&apos;s remaining meal swipes.
          Eventually, other features got added, including directions to nearby dining locations and when they&apos;re open, as well as what&apos;s on the menu at each location.
          There were also certain integrations with the operating system, including the today-widget and some plans to include Siri integration (&quot;Hey Siri, what&apos;s my Cat Cash balance?&quot;), and an Apple Watch app.
          I even localised the app into Simplified and Traditional Chinese, and French.
          I wanted to make the app a fully-fledged iOS app experience, and definitely learned a lot about really specific parts of mobile app design and development that you just wouldn&apos;t think about unless you went through it.
        </p>
        <p>Some thoughts off the top of my head:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>How do you present all this information in a clean way, but also without making the user do a single tap to get what they need? Empathy is key in design.</li>
          <li>How do you translate a specific, local concept like &quot;meal exchange/equivalency&quot; into another language, like Chinese and French?</li>
          <li>How do you balance the wants of the user, like an Android version, with my selfish want to implement niche things like localisation and iOS integration, instead? Sorry, user :)</li>
          <li>Is this entrepreneurship, a public service, or my own playground? It definitely didn&apos;t earn any money.</li>
          <li>Turns out Apple is pretty strict when it comes to In-App Purchases, as frustrating as it was to work with such a buggy library.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The code has gotten really messy from years of me throwing features in, here and there.
          It might be a good thing that I can spare someone the torment of trying to pick up this project.
          That being said, I would never have been able to launch this if I waited until it was perfect &mdash; it would never be.
          Sometimes you just need to lower your impossible standards to make progress, and that&apos;s okay.
        </p>
